In Python, abstract methods are implemented using the `abc` (Abstract Base Classes) module.

```python
import abc

class Shape(object):
    __metaclass__ = abc.ABCMeta

    @abc.abstractmethod
    def area(self, input):
        """Method to calculate area — must be implemented by subclasses."""
        return

class Circle(Shape):
    def area(self, radius):
        return 3.14 * radius * radius
```

Decorating a method with @abc.abstractmethod makes it abstract. Any subclass that does not override this method cannot be instantiated — Python will raise a TypeError.

`super()` is used to call a method from the parent (base) class without explicitly naming it. It is especially useful in inheritance to ensure the parent class is properly initialised.

```python
class Base(object):
    def __init__(self):
        print("Base created")

class ChildA(Base):
    def __init__(self):
        Base.__init__(self)          # explicit call — old style

class ChildB(Base):
    def __init__(self):
        super(ChildB, self).__init__()  # using super() — preferred style

ChildA()
ChildB()
```

Output:
Base created
Base created

`super()` makes code more maintainable — if the base class changes, you don't need to update every explicit call. It also handles the Method Resolution Order (MRO) correctly in multiple inheritance scenarios.

